In mathematics, the '''big q-Legendre polynomials''' are an [[orthogonal polynomials|orthogonal family]] of polynomials defined in terms of [[basic hypergeometric function|Heine's basic hypergeometric series]] as<ref>Roelof Koekoek, Peter Lesky, Rene Swattouw,Hypergeometric Orthogonal Polynomials and Their q-Analogues, p 443,Springer</ref>

:<math>\displaystyle   P_n(x;c;q)={}_3\phi_2(q^{-n},q^{n+1},x;q,cq;q,q) </math>.

They obey the orthogonality relation

: <math>\int_{cq}^q P_m(x;c;q)P_n(x;c;q) \, dx=q(1-c)\frac{1-q}{1-q^{2n+1}}\frac{(c^{-1}q;q)_n}{(cq;q)_n}(-cq^2)^n q^{n \choose 2}\delta_{mn}</math>

and have the limiting behavior

:<math>\displaystyle\lim_{q \to 1} P_n(x;0;q)=P_n(2x-1)</math>

where <math>P_n</math> is the <math>n</math>th [[Legendre polynomial]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

