== Lower and upper bounds ==
=== Lower bound === In September 2011, an anonymous poster of the internet imageboard [[4chan]] proved that the smallest superpermutation on ''n'' symbols (''n'' ≥ 2) has at least length ''n''! + (''n''−1)! + (''n''−2)! + ''n'' − 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warosu.org/sci/thread/S3751105#p3751197|title=Permutations Thread III|last1=Anonymous|first1=|date=17 September 2011|website=Warosu, a 4chan archive|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref> The proof for this lower bound came to the general public interest in October 2018, after mathematician and computer scientist Robin Houston tweeted about it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/24/18019464/4chan-anon-anime-haruhi-math-mystery|title=An anonymous 4chan post could help solve a 25-year-old math mystery|last1=Griggs|first1=Mary Beth|website=The Verge}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/robinhouston/status/1054637891085918209|title=A curious situation. The best known lower bound... (1054637891085918209)|last1=Houston|first1=Robin|website=Twitter|language=en|accessdate=27 October 2018}}</ref> On 25 October 2018, Robin Houston, Jay Pantone, and Vince Vatter posted a refined version of this proof in OEIS.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oeis.org/A180632/a180632.pdf|title=A lower bound on the length of the shortest superpattern|author1=Anonymous 4chan poster|last2=Houston|first2=Robin|date=October 25, 2018|website=OEIS|accessdate=27 October 2018|last3=Pantone|first3=Jay|last4=Vatter|first4=Vince}}</ref>
=== Upper bound === On 20 October 2018, by adapting a construction by Aaron Williams for constructing [[Hamiltonian path|Hamiltonian paths]] through the [[Cayley graph]] of the [[symmetric group]],<ref>{{Cite arXiv|arxiv=1307.2549v3|first=Williams|last=Aaron|title=Hamiltonicity of the Cayley Digraph on the Symmetric Group Generated by σ = (1 2 ... n) and τ = (1 2)}}</ref> [[Greg Egan]] devised an algorithm to produce superpermutations of length ''n''! + (''n''−1)! + (''n''−2)! + (''n''−3)! + ''n'' − 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gregegan.net/SCIENCE/Superpermutations/Superpermutations.html|title=Superpermutations|author=Egan|first=Greg|date=|year=20 October 2018|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref> Up to 2018, these are the smallest superpermutations known for ''n'' ≥ 7.
==See also== *[[Superpattern]], a permutation that contains each permutation of ''n'' symbols as a [[permutation pattern]]
