{{infobox graph | name = Watkins snark | image = [[Image:Watkins snark.svg|220px]] | image_caption = The Watkins snark | namesake = J. J. Watkins | vertices = 50 | edges = 75 | girth = 5 | diameter = 7 | radius = 7 | automorphisms = 5 | chromatic_number = 3 | chromatic_index = 4 | properties = [[Snark (graph theory)|Snark]] |book thickness=3|queue number=2}}
In the [[mathematics|mathematical]] field of [[graph theory]], the '''Watkins snark''' is a [[snark (graph theory)|snark]] with 50 [[vertex (graph theory)|vertices]] and 75 [[edge (graph theory)|edge]]s.<ref>{{MathWorld|title=Watkins Snark|urlname=WatkinsSnark}}</ref><ref>Watkins, J. J. and Wilson, R. J. "A Survey of Snarks." In Graph Theory, Combinatorics, and Applications (Ed. Y. Alavi, G. Chartrand, [[Ortrud Oellermann|O. R. Oellermann]], and [[A. J. Schwenk]]). New York: Wiley, pp. 1129-1144, 1991</ref> It was discovered by John J. Watkins in 1989.<ref>Watkins, J. J. "Snarks." Ann. New York Acad. Sci. 576, 606-622, 1989.</ref>
As a snark, the Watkins graph is a connected, [[Bridge (graph theory)|bridgeless]] [[cubic graph]] with [[chromatic index]] equal to 4. The Watkins snark is also [[planar graph|non-planar]] and [[hamiltonian graph|non-hamiltonian]]. It has book thickness 3 and queue number 2.<ref>Wolz, Jessica; ''Engineering Linear Layouts with SAT''. Master Thesis, University of Tübingen, 2018</ref>
Another well known snark on 50 vertices is the [[Szekeres snark]], the fifth known snark, discovered by [[George Szekeres]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Szekeres, G.|authorlink=George Szekeres|title=Polyhedral decompositions of cubic graphs|journal=Bull. Austral. Math. Soc.|volume=8|issue=03|pages=367&ndash;387|year=1973|doi=10.1017/S0004972700042660}}</ref>
